4 (6) Persons who are working in barbershops and are licensed or certified by the
5 State Board of Cosmetic Art Examiners pursuant to Chapter 88B of the
6 General Statutes, provided that those persons shall comply with G.S. 86B-31.
7 (7) Inmates under the jurisdiction of the North Carolina Department of Adult
8 Correction.
9 (8) Persons who are employed by barbershops and whose duties are expressly
10 confined to the shampooing or blow drying of hair, provided that the person
11 shall comply with G.S. 86B-31."
12 SECTION 3.(a) Transition from Licenses to Certifications. – The following
13 provisions shall govern the transition from natural hair care specialist licenses previously
14 required for practice under Chapter 88B of the General Statutes to infection control certifications
15 for natural hair care specialists under this act:
16 (1) Automatic conversion. – All individuals holding valid natural hair care
17 specialist licenses issued by the North Carolina Board of Cosmetic Art
18 Examiners as of October 1, 2026, shall automatically be deemed to hold the
19 equivalent infection control certification under Chapter 88B of the General
20 Statutes, as amended by this act, without further examination, application,
21 fees, or additional qualification requirements. The Board shall provide any
22 individual who is deemed to hold an infection control certification under this
23 subsection with an infection control certification free of charge.
24 (2) Pending applications. – Notwithstanding any other provision of law, any
25 application for a natural hair care specialist license submitted to the Board
26 prior to October 1, 2026, and still pending on that date shall be granted as an
27 infection control certification if the applicant meets all of the following
28 requirements:
29 a. Successful completion of at least 300 hours of a natural hair care
30 curriculum in an approved cosmetic art school.
31 b. Payment of the fees required by G.S. 88B-20.
32 SECTION 3.(b) Transition from Apprentice Licenses to Cosmetologist Licenses. –
33 The following provisions shall govern the transition from apprentice licenses previously required
34 for practice under Chapter 88B of the General Statutes to cosmetologist licenses under this act:
35 (1) Automatic conversion. – All individuals holding apprentice licenses issued by
36 the North Carolina Board of Cosmetic Art Examiners as of October 1, 2026,
37 shall automatically be deemed to hold a cosmetologist license without further
38 examination, application, fees, or additional qualification requirements.
39 (2) Pending applications. – Notwithstanding any other provision of law, any
40 application for an apprentice license submitted to the Board prior to October
41 1, 2026, and still pending on that date shall be granted as a cosmetologist
42 license if the applicant meets all of the following requirements:
43 a. Successful completion of at least 1,000 hours of a cosmetology
44 curriculum in an approved cosmetic art school, as certified by sworn
45 affidavit of three licensed cosmetologists or by other evidence
46 satisfactory to the Board.
47 b. Passage of an examination conducted by the Board.
48 c. Payment of the fees required by G.S. 88B-20.
49 (3) Renewal of licenses. – Upon expiration of an apprentice license, the Board
50 shall permit individuals to renew their credential as a cosmetologist license
51 without resubmission or additional qualifications.
Page 10 Senate Bill 808-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 SECTION 3.(c) Rulemaking. – The North Carolina Board of Cosmetic Art
2 Examiners shall adopt rules to implement the provisions of this act. The Board shall prominently
3 post on its publicly available website information about all of the following:
4 (1) The elimination of the apprentice license and transition to cosmetologist
5 licensure.
6 (2) The elimination of the natural hair care specialist license and transition to
7 certification.
8 (3) The requirement for completion of the infection control course for newly
9 certified natural hair care specialists.
10 (4) Clear instructions for accessing at least one free Board-approved infection
11 control course that satisfies the requirements for infection control certification
12 for natural hair care specialists.
13 SECTION 3.(d) Rulemaking. – The North Carolina Board of Barber and Electrolysis
14 Examiners may adopt rules to implement Section 2 of this act.
15 SECTION 4. Sections 1 and 2 of this act become effective October 1, 2026. The
16 remainder of this act is effective when it becomes law.
